@node "Install" "Installation"
Installation has to be done manually at the moment, but it's really quite
simple as there are only 2-3 files that need to be copied:

@{b}SoloControl@{ub} - this is the main program, so it's probably best to copy it to
somewhere in your search path (e.g. C:).

@{b}SoloControl.guide@{ub} - the documentation may be copied anywhere you want (e.g.
HELP:).

@{b}Rexx/LogSoloStats.rexx@{ub} - installation of this ARexx script is completely
optional.  Again, it may be copied anywhere you want. Note that you will
need to alter the variables at the top of the script to match your own
personal preferences.  See the @{"logging connection stats example" link "StatsLog" 0} for details
on what the script is for.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Available features & usage"
SoloControl is a shell based utility, and should not be run via the
Workbench.  SoloControl has a number of features, that can be used by
specifying the corresponding command line option.  What's more, you can mix
and match any of the options in a single call - demonstrated in the
examples below.  Also of note is that if you do not specify certain
options, the corresponding settings in the Solo will remain unchanged.

Although SoloControl can be run manually, it has been designed so that it
can easily be used by other programs, either directly or via ARexx scripts,
and that's where SoloControl's true power can be exploited.  See the
@{"examples" link "Examples" 0} for some ideas, and sample command lines.

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow}Command template:@{fg text}@{bg back}

  DEVICE/A,UNIT/N/A,SETCLOCK/S,DAY,DATE,TIME,CALLMONITOR/T,ANS/T,
  ANSRINGS/N/K,AUTOANSON/N/K,POWERSAVE/T,GETSTATS/S,GETCALLS/S,
  ERASECALLS/S,BAUDRATE/K/N,QUIET/S

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow}Required args:@{fg text}@{bg back}

  @{b}DEVICE@{ub}       Name of device driver (e.g. serial.device)

  @{b}UNIT@{ub}         Device unit number (e.g. 0)

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow}Optional:@{fg text}@{bg back}

  @{b}SETCLOCK@{ub}     Set Solo's clock to current system time (or specify
               time/date in the usual AmigaDOS format)

  @{b}CALLMONITOR@{ub}  Switch call monitoring on/off (same as pressing FAX +
               SPEAKER-PHONE buttons on the Solo)

  @{b}ANS@{ub}          Switch answerphone on/off (same as pressing ANS)

  @{b}ANSRINGS@{ub}     Number of rings before answering machine answers

  @{b}AUTOANSON@{ub}    Number of rings before the Solo automatically switches ANS
               mode on, should it be switched off (20 rings is the factory
               default setting)

  @{b}POWERSAVE@{ub}    Toggle power saving mode on/off

  @{b}GETSTATS@{ub}     Print statistics on any previous modem connections

  @{b}GETCALLS@{ub}     List all calls that are present in the Solo's caller id log

  @{b}ERASECALLS@{ub}   Delete all calls present in the Solo's caller id log,
               having the same effect as pressing the ERASE + CALLER ID
               buttons (warning: once erased, the data cannot be
               retrieved)

  @{b}BAUDRATE@{ub}     Baud rate / speed to use with the modem (defaults
               automatically to 38400 for the internal serial port and
               115200 for third-party serial ports)

  @{b}QUIET@{ub}        Don't print any status messages
@endnode

@node "Examples" "Examples"
SoloControl can be put to a number of useful uses, and when used by other
programs either directly, or via ARexx scripts, SoloControl can be put to
some very good uses - as can be seen in the detailed examples. Of course,
there are times when you'll want to run SoloControl manually, and if you
are not sure about how to use it, see the simple examples below.

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow}Detailed examples:@{fg text}@{bg back}

 1. @{"Keeping the Solo's clock up to date" link "Clock" 0}
 2. @{"Keeping logs of your connection statistics" link "StatsLog" 0}

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow}Simple examples:@{fg text}@{bg back}

 solocontrol serial.device 0
   display current settings

 solocontrol serial.device 0 setclock
   sets Solo's clock to current system time

 solocontrol serial.device 0 setclock 17-Feb-00 20:00
   sets Solo's clock to 17 Feb 2000, 8pm

 solocontrol serial.device 0 callmonitor=off
   switch call monitoring off

 solocontrol serial.device 0 ans=on ansrings=5
   switch answerphone on, and set number of rings to 5

 solocontrol serial.device 0 setclock ans off callmonitor on powersave=on
   set clock, switch answerphone off, call monitoring + power save mode on

 solocontrol serial.device 0 getstats >> solostats.txt
   get connection statistics from Solo, and append them to solostats.txt
@endnode

@node "Clock" "Keeping your Solo's clock up to date"
The Pace 56 Solo relies on CallerID data to keep it's clock up-to-date, so
if you have subscribed to your telco's CallerID (aka Caller Display)
service, you can be sure that incoming calls will be correctly time-tagged.
However, if you don't (or can't) subscribe to a Caller ID service, you can
use SoloControl to keep your Solo's clock up-to-date.

In the simplest case, you could put the following in your s:user-startup
file, so that whenever you boot your machine up, you Solo's clock will be
set to the same time as your Amiga's system clock.

  SoloControl serial.device 0 setclock

However, if you're Amiga's clock tends to lose/gain time, or you simply
want to keep it accurate, then you may want to use your TCP/IP stack (e.g.
Miami, Genesis) to @{"synchronise your Amiga clock to an accurate source" link "Genesis-Amiga synch" 0} when
you go on-line, and then use SoloControl to @{"set the Solo's clock" link "Amiga-Pace synch" 0} as you go
off-line.  Both Amiga and modem then have their clocks set automatically
during an on-line session.

After setting the above up, you may want to @{"test everything out" link "Genesis-SoloControl" 0} to check
that everything works before you relax in the knowledge that your Amiga and
modem will be set correctly.
@endnode

@node "Genesis-Amiga synch" "Using Miami/Genesis to sychronise your Amiga clock"
@{fg shine}@{bg shadow} Miami @{fg text}@{bg back}

 1. Goto the TCP/IP settings section (in Miami Deluxe, goto your
    chosen interface first and then click the TCP/IP settings button)
 2. Click on the "Get time" checkbox, to enable it
 3. Enter the address of an academic or military internet Time Server in
    the text box e.g. ntp2a.mcc.ac.uk
 4. Unfortunately, Miami does not have an option to save the time to your
    battery-backed clock, but you can accomplish this by adding
    "setclock save" as your Online event, or adding it to your ARexx
    script if you have already set it up to run one.
 5. Save your settings

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow} Genesis @{fg text}@{bg back}

 1. Select to edit your @{"interface in GenesisPrefs" link "Genesis-Interface" 0}
 2. Of the several tabs shown, pick "Service"
 3. Click in the boxes to tick "Sync clock" and "Save Time"
 4. Enter the address of an academic or military internet Time Server in
    the text box e.g. ntp2a.mcc.ac.uk
 5. Okay and Save prefs.

Next time you connect, Genesis will pickup the time from the selected net
clock and save it to your  Amiga internal clock. You should see a message
"querying time server" just before the dial-up section closes.
@endnode

@node "Amiga-Pace synch" "Using Genesis and SoloControl to set your Pace 56 Solo clock"
@{fg shine}@{bg shadow} Miami @{fg text}@{bg back}

 1. Goto the Events settings section (in Miami Deluxe, goto your chosen
    interface first and then click the Events button)
 2. Click on the "Get time" checkbox, to enable it
 3. If you don't already have an Online event, toggle the cycle gadget
    to Shell and enter SoloControl device/unit/setclock arguments after
    the file path (e.g. SoloControl serial.device 0 setclock) - you may
    want to add additional arguments.
 4. If you want visual confirmation of SoloControl's activities, follow
    the arguments with  " > con://///wait/close". The results appear in a
    window on the Workbench.
 5. However, if you already have an offline event, things are a little
    bit trickier.  Presuming you have chosen to run your own ARexx
    script when going offline, you can simple enter the command, as
    above, in you ARexx script.
 6. Save your settings

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow} Genesis @{fg text}@{bg back}

 1. Select to edit your @{"interface in GenesisPrefs" link "Genesis-Interface" 0}
 2. Of the several tabs shown, pick "Events"
 3. Interface should show Online events- toggle to show Offline Active
    events
 4. Click Add (be sure that CLI is the selected type- see bottom right;
    toggle if needed)
 5. Choose SoloControl file location by browsing then edit the adjacent
    text box to add the SoloControl device/unit/setclock arguments after
    the file path (e.g. SoloControl serial.device 0 setclock) - you may
    want to add additional arguments.
 7. If you want visual confirmation of SoloControl's activities, follow
    the arguments with  " > con://///wait/close". The results appear in a
    window on the Workbench.
 8. Okay and save prefs.

Next time Genesis goes offline, it will save the Amiga clock to the Pace 56
Solo. There may be a slight delay as SoloControl acts- the modem lights
will flash in sequence.
@endnode

@node "Genesis-Interface" "Selecting your interface in GenesisPrefs"
 1. Start Genesis and -with its menu bar active- use right mouse button to
    select Settings/Genesis
 2. Pick the "Interfaces" item listed by MUI and select yours (if there
    are several ISPs set up)
 3. Double click or press to Edit the interface
@endnode

@node "Genesis-SoloControl" "Testing that Miami/Genesis and.SoloControl work together"
How do you prove that it all works? Well if you've followed the suggestions
on setting the Amiga clock and the Pace 56 Solo clock, you could try the
following:

 1. Deliberately set your Amiga clock to the wrong time (e.g. via
    sys:prefs/time, setting the clock out by 30 minutes say)
 2. Mis-set your Pace Solo clock: e.g. issue a command like
    solocontrol serial.device 0 setclock 17-Feb-90 20:00
 3. On the Pace 56 Solo, hold down the "ANN" key and press the "Fax" key -
    the modem should speak the set time.
 4: Go on-line, and when the session is finished, disconnect.
 5: Use "ANN" plus "FAX" to check that the Pace 56 Solo time has been
    corrected
 6: Check time prefs or use a clock to confirm that the Amiga
    clock coincides with the Solo.
@endnode

@node "StatsLog" "Logging your connection statistics"
I use SoloControl's GETSTATS feature to log information all of my
connections, and to also display the statistics of my last connection in a
window when I go offline.  This can be very handy, especially if you're
experiencing connection problems with your ISP.  Having set this up myself,
I was surprised to find that my connections to Freeserve are actually a lot
worse than they used to be, despite always connecting at the same speed (in
my case, the Solo is having to fallback from 45333 to speeds like 41333 or
even 31200).

To make things easier, I have provided an ideal way to monitor your
connections, via an ARexx script which is included with SoloControl
(LogSoloStat.rexx). You will need to edit the variables at the top of the
script to match your own setup and preferences.  This can then be added to
your Miami or Genesis offline events, so that the script is called each
time you go offline. See your TCP/IP stack documentation, or the
@{"clock synchronisation" link "Clock" 0} example for Miami + Genesis details.

That's all you really need to know, but if you're curious of what the
commands in the script do, here's a simple walkthrough:

 - SoloControl squirrelserial.device 0 getstats > t:SoloStats.txt

This gets the stats from the Solo using SoloControl and saves them to
t:SoloStats.txt

 - c:type t:SoloStats.txt > "CON:20/564/410/250/Connection stats/WAIT/
   CLOSE/NOFNC/NOREVIEW/NOSHOWDIR/NOICONIFY/INACTIVE"

This shows these stats in a CON window.

 - c:date >> dh0:logs/SoloStats.log
 - c:type t:SoloStats.txt >> dh0:logs/SoloStats.log
 - echo "" >> dh0:logs/SoloStats.log

And finally, it saves the current time/date to the SoloStats.log file, then
adds in the current stats, followed by a blank line.
@endnode

